Raw dev notes -- Jan-Feb 2026

Not every week has a main quest. Sometimes the most productive thing you can do is
chip away at the backlog of small tasks that have been piling up. Here's a roundup
from a period where I bounced between a bunch of smaller projects.

Electron Audio Converter:
A desktop app I built for batch audio format conversion (MP3, WAV, FLAC, etc.).
Found and fixed a bug where MP3 bitrate calculations were wrong when targeting a
specific file size -- it was using the wrong formula for variable bitrate. Also
regenerated the app icon with proper multi-resolution sizes. Windows is picky about
its .ico files -- you need multiple resolutions embedded in one file or the icon
looks blurry at certain display scales.

Dev Environment Bootstrap:
This one I'm excited about. Created a Python project template with everything I wish
every project started with: structured JSON logging with both human-readable and
machine-parseable formatters, environment-based config management, a CI workflow,
VS Code settings with proper Python analysis, pyproject.toml instead of setup.py.
The idea is to never set up these basics from scratch again. Already used it twice.

GitHub Profile and Blog SEO:
Updated my profile README, added an MIT license to the profile repo, set up og:image
and meta keywords for the blog. Small things, but they matter for visibility when
someone lands on your GitHub.

The common thread: none of these felt productive in the moment, but looking back,
this kind of steady maintenance is what keeps a portfolio healthy. It's the developer
equivalent of cleaning your apartment -- doesn't feel exciting, but you notice when
it's done.
